SECTION 2 — Ecosystem Concept History
Who coined what — important for NET exams
A.G. Tansley (1935) British ecologist Arthur George Tansley coined the term "ECOSYSTEM" in
1935. He defined it as "the whole system including not only the
organism-complex but also the whole complex of physical factors forming
what we call the environment." Published in the journal Ecology. This is the
MOST IMPORTANT fact to remember.
Karl Möbius (1877) Described the concept of a "Biocoenosis" (biological community) while
studying oyster beds in Germany. Precursor to the ecosystem concept.
Forbes (1887) Described the lake as a "microcosm" — a self-regulating unit. Early precursor
to ecosystem thinking.
Charles Elton (1927) Described food chains, food webs, and ecological niches. His book "Animal
Ecology" (1927) laid foundation for understanding ecosystem function.
Eugene Odum
(1953/1971)
Wrote the landmark textbook "Fundamentals of Ecology" (1953). Defined
ecosystem as "any unit that includes all the organisms in a given area
interacting with the physical environment so that a flow of energy leads to
clearly defined trophic structure, biotic diversity and material cycles." He is
called the Father of Modern Ecology.
Howard T. Odum (1956) Eugene Odum's brother. Developed energy circuit language and used
thermodynamics to model ecosystem energy flows. Pioneer of systems
ecology.
Raymond Lindeman
(1942)
Proposed the concept of trophic dynamics — how energy flows through
food chains with ~10% efficiency at each level. His paper on Cedar Bog Lake
is a classic in ecology.
n EXAM TIP: A.G. Tansley coined "Ecosystem" in 1935. Eugene Odum = "Father of Modern
Ecology". Lindeman = trophic dynamics / 10% energy transfer rule. These 3 are asked DIRECTLY in
NET exams.
