4.2 Edaphic Factors (Soil-Related)
Edaphic comes from the Greek word edaphos meaning "ground" or "soil". Edaphic factors are soil-related
properties that influence which organisms can live in an area:
Edaphic Factor Ecological Significance
Soil Texture Proportion of sand, silt, clay. Sandy soil = well-drained, poor nutrients. Clay soil =
waterlogged, rich nutrients.
Soil pH Acidity/alkalinity. Most plants prefer pH 6-7. Acidic soils (pH<6) suit conifers, heathland;
alkaline (pH>7) suit grassland.
Soil Moisture Water-holding capacity. Determines if area is a wetland, grassland, or desert.
Organic Matter / Humus Decomposed organic material. Improves soil structure, water retention, nutrient
availability.
Mineral Nutrients N, P, K, Ca, Mg, S. Nitrogen (N) is most commonly limiting. Phosphorus (P) limits aquatic
productivity.
Soil Depth Determines rooting depth. Shallow soils limit large trees; deep soils support diverse root
systems.
Soil Organisms Bacteria, fungi, earthworms, nematodes — maintain soil health and nutrient cycling.
