Fig 8: Odum's 4-Component Model of Ecosystem Structure
Eugene Odum (1971) classified all ecosystem components into 4 groups. This is the standard framework
used in ecology textbooks and is the most frequently tested framework in UGC NET:
1. Abiotic
Substances
Includes: (a) Inorganic substances — COn, HnO, On, Nn, minerals, salts; (b)
Organic compounds — proteins, carbohydrates, lipids, humus that link biotic and
abiotic components; (c) Climate regime — temperature, rainfall, sunlight
patterns.
2. Producers Autotrophic organisms — mainly green plants on land and phytoplankton in
water. They synthesise complex organic substances from simple inorganic ones
using solar energy. They are also called transducers because they convert
solar energy to chemical energy.
3. Consumers
(Macro-consumers /
Phagotrophs)
Heterotrophic organisms that ingest organic matter. Primary consumers
(herbivores), Secondary consumers (carnivores), Tertiary consumers (top
carnivores), Omnivores. Also includes parasites which consume living hosts.
4. Decomposers
(Micro-consumers /
Saprotrophs)
Heterotrophic organisms — mainly bacteria and fungi — that break down
complex organic molecules of dead organisms. They absorb some
decomposition products and release inorganic nutrients to the environment. Also
called Reducers or Transformers.
