n KEY FACTS FOR UGC NET — Unit 3.3
4 1. "Ecosystem" coined by A.G. Tansley in 1935 (published in journal Ecology)
4 2. Eugene Odum = Father of Modern Ecology; defined ecosystem fully in 1953/1971
4 3. Raymond Lindeman (1942) proposed 10% energy transfer rule (trophic efficiency)
4 4. Odum's 4 components: (1) Abiotic substances (2) Producers (3) Consumers (4) Decomposers
4 5. Producers = TL-1, Primary consumers = TL-2, Secondary = TL-3, Tertiary = TL-4
4 6. Only ~10% energy transfers to next trophic level; 90% lost as heat
4 7. Decomposers = bacteria + fungi; also called saprotrophs, micro-consumers, reducers
4 8. Detritivores (earthworm, millipede) are different from decomposers (bacteria, fungi)
4 9. GPP = total photosynthesis; NPP = GPP - plant respiration
4 10. Chemoautotrophs: Nitrosomonas (NHn®NOn), Nitrobacter (NOn®NOn) — use chemical
energy
4 11. Phytoplankton = main producers in aquatic ecosystems; green plants = main producers on land
4 12. Edaphic = soil-related abiotic factors (Greek: edaphos = ground)
4 13. Humus = dark organic material formed during decomposition; improves soil fertility
4 14. Phosphorus is most commonly limiting nutrient in aquatic ecosystems; nitrogen on land
4 15. Ecosystem is an OPEN system — energy flows through; nutrients cycle within
